definition.value: A cinnamate ester rusulting from the formal condensation of cinnamic acid with any alkyl alcohol.
A short-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of butyric acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A xylose of ring-opened form having L-configuration.
An aromatic alcohol that consists of benzene bearing a single hydroxymethyl substituent.
Sucrose is a disaccharide formed by glucose and fructose units joined by an acetal oxygen bridge from hemiacetal of glucose to the hemiketal of the fructose.
A halide anion formed when chlorine picks up an electron to form an an anion.
An elemental molecule consisting of two trivalently-bonded nitrogen atoms.
An alkylamine in which the alkyl group is substituted by an aromatic hydrocarbyl group.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from deprotonation of the carboxy group of keto-phenylpyruvic acid.
A butenedioic acid in which the C=C double bond has E geometry. It is an intermediate metabolite in the citric acid cycle.
An L-alpha-amino acid; the L-isomer of lysine.
A pseudohalide anion obtained by deprotonation of the thiol group of thiocyanic acid.
The D-enantiomer of galacturonic acid. It is the main component of pectin.
A dihydroxybenzoic acid that is  benzoic acid substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 2 and 3. It occurs naturally in Phyllanthus acidus and in the aquatic fern Salvinia molesta.
A glyceride in which any two of the R groups (positions not specified) are acyl groups while the remaining R group can be either H or an alkyl group.
An optically active form of glutamine having L-configuration.

'Lipids' is a loosely defined term for substances of biological origin that are soluble in nonpolar solvents. They consist of saponifiable lipids, such as glycerides (fats and oils) and phospholipids, as well as nonsaponifiable lipids, principally steroids.
A 3-hydroxymethylcephalosporin having a (5-amino-5-carboxypentanoyl)amino group at the 7-position.
A ketoaldonic acid phosphate consisting of 3-deoxy-D-manno-oct-2-ulosonic acid having a phospho group at the 8-position.
A dihydroxybenzoic acid where the hydroxy groups are at the 4- and 5-positions together with a hexaprenyl group at the 3-position.
Any polysaccharide containing a substantial proportion of aminomonosaccharide residues.
An N-acylglycine in which the acyl group is specified as benzoyl.
An optically active form of 4-hydroxyproline having L-trans-configuration.
An alcohol that consists of cyclohexane bearing a single hydroxy substituent. The parent of the class of cyclohexanols.
A monocarboxylic acid that is acetic acid in which one of the methyl hydrogens is substituted by a 4-hydroxyphenyl group.
An iminium betaine that is the conjugate base of N-methylnicotinic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
The trans-isomer of 2-coumaric acid.

An alkane-alpha,omega-diamine comprising a straight-chain pentane core with amino substitutents at positions 1 and 5. A colourless syrupy liquid diamine with a distinctive unpleasant odour, it is a homologue of putresceine and is formed by the bacterial decarboxylation of lysine that occurs during protein hydrolysis during putrefaction of animal tissue. It is also found in plants such as soyabean.
The phosphate of choline; and the parent compound of the phosphocholine family.
Any six-carbon monosaccharide which in its linear form contains either an aldehyde group at position 1 (aldohexose) or a ketone group at position 2 (ketohexose).
A  benzenediol comprising of a benzene core carrying two hydroxy substituents ortho to each other.
A tertiary amine that is ammonia in which each hydrogen atom is substituted by an methyl group.
An N(6')-acetylkanamycin derived from kanamycin B.
A maltose that has beta-configuration at the reducing end anomeric centre.
A ketoaldonic acid phosphate consisting of 2-dehydro-3-deoxy-D-arabino-heptonic acid having a phospho group at the 7-position.
A biomacromolecule consisting of large numbers of monosaccharide residues linked glycosidically. This term is commonly used only for those containing more than ten monosaccharide residues.
A maltose that has alpha-configuration at the reducing end anomeric centre.
A monohydroxycinnamic acid in which the hydroxy substituent is located at C-2 of the phenyl ring.
An optically active form of 5-oxoproline having L-configuration.
An alpha-amino acid that is phenylalanine bearing a hydroxy substituent at position 4 on the phenyl ring.
The L-enantiomer of iditol.
A galactosamine phosphate that is N-acetyl-D-galactosamine substituted at position 1 by a monophosphate group.
